        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>31 Aug.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Charles</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I send you Div<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I have just been reading a novel I recommend you to try “The Hon Miss Ferrard”<ref target="#foot.f3"/>   I’m not at all sure you will like it but I’m quite sure Emma wont. She has lovely eyes &amp; does not say ten words in three volumes. There is a charming love scene in breaking in a colt. The third vol is by far the best &amp; one does not feel sure how it will end up to the very last. Some irish politics you’ll have to skip judiciously but that I believe Emma is an adept in.</p>
<p>Yours EAD</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the publication date of the novel (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The dividends were probably for shares that belonged to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin</ref>; Erasmus was one of the trustees of Emma’s property (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 3, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-779.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Solicitor?, 1 October 1844</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The novel appeared as <hi rend="italic">The Hon. Miss Ferrard</hi> ‘by the author of “Hogan, M.P.”’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10299.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">[Laffan] 1877</ref>). The author was later revealed to be Mary (May) Laffan. The novel was published in July 1877 (<hi rend="italic">Publishers’ Circular</hi>, 17 July 1877, p. 487).</note>
        </div>        
            
